article.description:
Olympian Dawn Staley scored 19 points in her last home game before heading to Athens, helping the Charlotte
Sting snap a four-game losing streak with a 70-41 victory over the Washington Mystics on Saturday.
article.headline: Staley scores 19 in victory
article.linkText: Sting rout Mystics and snap four-game slide
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Dawn Staley made sure her last WNBA game
before the Athens Olympics was a victory.

Staley, set to play on the U.S. women's Olympic team for the
third time, scored 19 points in her final home game before heading
to Greece, helping the Charlotte Sting snap a four-game losing
streak with a 70-41 victory over the Washington Mystics on
Saturday.

"I just tried to come out and attack and be aggressive,"
Staley said. "Fortunately, I was able to get to the basket and get
some easy shots. I hit the open shots and I got off more shots than
I normally do. We needed this game."

The Mystics absorbed their most lopsided loss of the season
without leading scorer Chamique Holdsclaw. Holdsclaw did not travel
with the team because of "personal reasons," according to a team
spokesman.

Staley scored nine points in a 17-0 run during a seven-minute
span in the first half, helping Charlotte take a 17-6 lead with
9:09 left.

The Sting built a 31-9 lead before settling for a 15-point
halftime edge with Staley scoring 13 points.

The undermanned Mystics trailed by as many as 32 in the second
half. Holdsclaw, who averages 19.3 points per game, missed the game
one night after being held to nine points on 3-of-17 shooting in a
home win over Minnesota.

"Right now, I don't know what her status is," Mystics coach
Michael Adams said. "Obviously she's out for personal reasons and
hopefully she'll be back soon. That's it, that's all I know."

Washington was also without starting point guard Tamicha
Jackson, who's on the injured list with a strained knee, and Stacey
Dales-Schuman, who missed her third straight game with a sore heel.

Alana Beard had 19 points for the Mystics (10-13), who have lost
four of five. Nicole Powell added a career-high 14 points for the
Sting (11-11), who held a 36-17 rebounding edge.

"Teams face adversity and we have to overcome that," Beard
said. "We didn't walk into this game thinking we were going to
lose. We just have to fight through this."

Staley was honored before the game by Charlotte mayor Pat
McCrory, who proclaimed it "Dawn Staley Olympian Day."

McCrory referred to Staley as "Dawn Stanley" four times during
the ceremony. Staley shrugged off the miscue and went on to shoot
8-for-11 in the game.

But Staley thinks she won't soon forget the mayor's mistake.

"It's going to be a long-running joke," she said.

"(Stanley) is her new name," teammate Allison Feaster said.
